\f0\fs24 \cf0 One difficulty of approaches based on family tree similarities is that the phylogenetic trees of all protein families retain a degree of similarity to the archetypal \'93tree of life\'94 that represents the global evolutionary relationships between organisms. Consequently, any pair of family trees has a \'93basal\'94 level of similarity, regardless of whether the corresponding proteins are functionally interacting. Some approaches to correct for this organismal speciation use the evolutionary distances between the corresponding species to normalize each protein\'96protein distance\super 67-69\nosupersub . Another alternative is to infer the background similarity not from the general species tree but from the main tendencies of actual data from many protein families\super 70,71\nosupersub .\
