\f2 \cf0 The similarity between two phylogenetic trees is influenced by the speciation process, and therefore there is a certain \'91\'91background\'92\'92 similarity between trees of any proteins, no matter if they interact or not. Different statistical techniques have been developed to account for \'91\'91phylogenetic subtraction\'92\'92 [35]. Simplified versions of this approach were introduced recently to account for the background similarity in protein interaction prediction [36\'9638]. According to one of them [36], the \'91\'91background\'92\'92 tree is constructed from the 16S rRNA sequences and is considered to be a canonical tree of life. The final distance matrices are obtained by subtracting the rescaled rRNA-based distances from the evolutionary distances obtained from the original phylogenetic trees. It has been shown that this method finds 50% of real interacting proteins at a 6.4% false positive rate compared with the 16.5% false positive rate obtained using methods which do not take into account evolutionary distances and the \'91\'91background\'92\'92 canonical tree [29,30].\
